<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-02T07:25:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-02T07:25:00-05:00" n="48" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/3838: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Ethiopia</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Engert</hi></persName>)
                                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Addis
                                            Ababa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-02T15:00:00+02:35">March 2, 1936—3
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 4:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>127. It is unofficially admitted very serious fighting has occurred
                                in the North and that Italian claim that Amba Alagi has been taken
                                may be correct.</p>
                            <p>Official communiqué denies categorically rumors that Emperor is ill
                                or wounded or that he intends to leave the country.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>